        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        M. Smith, Colonel of the Ardes in Ireland, did maruell at nothing more in all Liuie, then at this discreete, &amp; respectiue oration of 
                        Annibal, after so manie braue resolutions, impetuous aduentures, &amp; maine battels.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Thomas Smith"/>
                <person name="Hannibal"/>
                <book title="Ab Urbe Condita"/>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                       " " Sapiens Annibalis oratjo. ^ plena considerata[e], et veterana[e] prudentia[e].
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Hannibal"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                A wise speech of Hannibal, full of thoughtful and experienced prudence.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Ecc&egrave; tandem Annibal, cautior consiliarius, qu&agrave;m ferocior Dux. Quid mirum, si Annibal Fabium fecerit politicum, et 
                        pragmaticum; cum Scipio Annibalem ipsium faciat Oratorem, et Philosophum? Alius est iuuenilis Fortitudinis spiritus: alius virilis 
                        prudentia[e]: alius senilis Temperantia[e]. Et sua cuiq[ue] phrasis, suus stilus; magis, minusue temperatus, ac quodammod&ograve; froenatus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Hannibal"/>
                <person name="Fabius Maximus"/>
                <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Look: in the end Hannibal was a very cautious counsellor, rather than a very fierce leader. It is no surprise that Hannibal would turn Fabius 
                into a politician and pragmatic, while Scipio makes Hannibal into an orator and philosopher? The one is a spirit of youthful courage, the other
                one of mature prudence, and the third one of aged restraint. And each of them has their own way of expression and style; more, or less 
                controlled, and bridled, so to speak.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
